What I changed
I focused on the scorer rather than expanding the dataset.
The main change was to stop the judge from treating a long answer holistically when one embedded harmful claim could still disenfranchise a voter.
I added harm_flags and fatal_error so the output records specific participation-risk errors, such as wrong deadlines, postmark-vs-arrival mistakes, invented ID requirements, and wrong eligibility rules.
I also fixed a Windows UTF-8 bug and removed the OpenAI package dependency so the script is easier to run.

Why this tradeoff
The single worst structural issue is that the benchmark is small and lacks calibrated human labels, but that is not fixable well in a short work sample.
The best feasible fix was improving the scorer's construct validity for the actual harm: one actionable wrong instruction can be enough to suppress a vote


Where the coding agent helped and what I checked
The agent helped inspect the repo quickly and patch the code.
I checked the actual data shape and caught that the repo failed locally because Python was reading UTF-8 JSONL with the Windows default codepage.
I kept the change small rather than rewriting the eval.


What I would do with ten times the time
Atomize the reference facts into claim-level labels.
Add a small human-labeled calibration set and measure judge agreement.
Make source-authority checking deterministic by domain.
Add adversarial prompts and multilingual variants.
Add a reliance study or simulated-impact model for how wrong answers translate into missed votes.


Final takeaway
The improved scorer does not make the benchmark complete, but it better matches the risk scenario: detecting harmful, participation-suppressing voting misinformation rather than merely scoring whether an answer is mostly correct.
